This is a shell issue : use quotes around `&#39;stash@{xx}&#39;`

    git show &#39;stash@{1}&#39;

---

In Powershell for example : `{ cmd1; cmd2 }` defines a [script block](https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.core/about/about_script_blocks?view=powershell-7)

Here is an example of what I get :

    &gt; echo stash@{1}
    stash@
    1
    &gt; echo &#39;stash@{1}&#39;
    stash@{1}

If you used the SVG actually as a background and not as an image I expect that you also have used CSS. Asuming your image does not include the white borders, you could use this:

    .your-selector {
        background-image: url(&#39;your image&#39;);
        width: 100%;
        height: 100%;
        background-size: 100% 100%;
        background-position: 0 0;
        background-repeat: no-repeat;
    }

If your SVG does contain the white borders and you don&#39;t want to change your SVGyou can change the value of your `background-size: ..% ..%` to values that make the SVG fit.
